item.title: European Hospitals Hit Hard by Coronavirus Fear a Resurgence
item.description: As pressure on Europe’s hospitals eases with the number of coronavirus patients in intensive-care units decreasing, badly hit countries now face decisions about what to do with the extra wards they scrambled to build.

item.title: Oil Slump, Coronavirus Create a Perfect Storm for Nigeria's Economy
item.description: The crash in oil prices and the economic fallout from the coronavirus pose what could be an existential threat for Africa’s largest economy and biggest crude producer.

item.title: New Zealand Claims a Victory Over Coronavirus
item.description: The Pacific nation said it had effectively eliminated the disease from within its borders, the culmination of a tough social experiment, but a risk of new flare-ups remains.

item.title: Japan's Virus Cases Fall Sharply Without Compulsory Measures
item.description: Tokyo reported its lowest daily level of new coronavirus cases in more than three weeks, a fresh sign Japan may be succeeding in suppressing the outbreak without compulsory distancing and with limited testing.

item.title: North Korea's Kim Stays Out of Sight for Another Day
item.description: North Korean dictator Kim Jong Un remained absent Monday, as state media reported his thank-you letter to construction workers and Seoul officials reasserted that they believe he is alive.

item.title: Iran-Backed Groups Seek Public Support Through Coronavirus Fight
item.description: Groups in Lebanon and Iraq have mounted campaigns against the coronavirus as they seek to bolster their reputations and regain their footing after coming under pressure from popular protests.
